File: Seasoned cricketer, Vernon Philander is set to retire at the end of the Test series against England. JOHANNESBURG - Proteas all-rounder Vernon Philander has announced he will retire from all forms of international cricket at the end of the Test series against England. Philander has battled with injuries in recent years which have limited his game time with South Africa. READ: NZ Cricket file complaint with police over Archer abuse His career spanned over 12 years with 97 matches across all three formats. The 34-year-old has 261 wickets under his belt with 1784 runs scored. The Capetonian made his Proteas debut Test match against Australia in November 2011. He took an outstanding combined 8/78 including a famous spell of 5/15 that had the visitors bowled out for 47 in their second innings.